## Recommended usage path (application code)

Most app code should use `dropStore`, not providers directly.

From `src/stores/dropStore.ts`:

- `createDrop(payload)` chooses local/remote by `offlineMode`
- `getDrop(id)` routes by id prefix
- `resolveDropGraph(id)` routes by id prefix

### Example: share from UI (recommended)

```ts
const createDrop = useDropStore((state) => state.createDrop);
const hydrateOfflineMode = useDropStore((state) => state.hydrateOfflineMode);

await hydrateOfflineMode();

const result = await createDrop({
  content: markdown,
  metadata: {
    themeId,
    baseDropId,
    snapshotId,
  },
});

// result => { id, url, scope: "local" | "remote" }
```

## Direct provider usage (advanced)

Use this when building tests, custom workflows, or tooling.

### Create providers directly

```ts
import {
  createLocalDropProvider,
  createRemoteDropProvider,
} from "src/lib/drop/provider";

const local = createLocalDropProvider();
const remote = createRemoteDropProvider();

const localResult = await local.create({ content: "local note" });
const remoteResult = await remote.create({ content: "remote note" });
```

### Create a registry with shared crypto dependency

```ts
import { createDropProviderRegistry } from "src/lib/drop/provider";
import { createBrowserDropCrypto } from "src/lib/drop/browserDropCrypto";

const crypto = createBrowserDropCrypto();
const registry = createDropProviderRegistry({ crypto });

const provider = registry.forDropId(dropId);
const payload = await provider.get(dropId);
```

This mirrors production behavior where local and remote providers share one crypto port.

## End-to-end flow diagrams

### Architecture map

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  UI[Editor and DropView]
  Store[dropStore]
  Registry[DropProviderRegistry]

  Local[Local Provider]
  Remote[Remote Provider]
  Crypto[BrowserDropCrypto]
  LocalStorage[LocalDropStorage]
  GraphLocal[LineageGraphPort local cache]
  GraphRemote[LineageGraphPort remote cache]

  IDB[(IndexedDB drops + kv)]
  StoreApi[/POST /api/store/]
  GetApi[/GET /api/get/:id/]
  R2[(Cloudflare R2)]

  UI --> Store
  Store --> Registry

  Registry --> Local
  Registry --> Remote

  Local --> Crypto
  Remote --> Crypto

  Local --> LocalStorage --> IDB
  Remote --> StoreApi --> R2
  Remote --> GetApi --> R2

  Local --> GraphLocal --> IDB
  Remote --> GraphRemote --> IDB
```

### Online share (remote provider)

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
  participant UI
  participant Store as dropStore
  participant Remote as RemoteProvider
  participant Crypto as BrowserDropCrypto
  participant API as /api/store
  participant R2

  UI->>Store: createDrop(payload), offlineMode=false
  Store->>Remote: create(payload)
  Remote->>Crypto: seal(payload)
  Crypto-->>Remote: DropEnvelopeV1
  Remote->>API: POST encrypted envelope
  API->>API: optional provider signature
  API->>R2: put(id, envelope)
  API-->>Remote: {id, url}
  Remote-->>Store: {id, url, scope:"remote"}
  Store-->>UI: share link
```

### Offline share (local provider)

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
  participant UI
  participant Store as dropStore
  participant Local as LocalProvider
  participant Crypto as BrowserDropCrypto
  participant IDB as IndexedDB

  UI->>Store: createDrop(payload), offlineMode=true
  Store->>Local: create(payload)
  Local->>Crypto: seal(payload)
  Crypto-->>Local: DropEnvelopeV1
  Local->>IDB: putOfflineDrop(record)
  Local-->>Store: {id:"offline_*", url, scope:"local"}
  Store-->>UI: local-only share link
```

### Graph resolution with cache

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  Start[resolveGraph headId] --> Cache{cached graph exists?}
  Cache -- yes --> ReturnCached[return cached DropGraph]
  Cache -- no --> Walk[walk baseDropId chain via get]
  Walk --> Build[build headId rootId lineage nodes]
  Build --> Persist[cache in IndexedDB kv]
  Persist --> ReturnFresh[return computed DropGraph]
```

## How the provider scales

Scaling happens across four dimensions: traffic, compute, lineage, and codebase evolution.

### 1) Traffic scaling

- Offline traffic is absorbed by browser storage, so it does not hit server APIs.
- Remote traffic is stateless at the function layer and object-backed in R2.
- Reads and writes split naturally by id prefix and mode without branching in UI code.

### 2) Compute scaling

- Encryption/decryption happens in the browser (`BrowserDropCrypto`), which offloads server CPU.
- Server-side remote provider path mainly validates, optionally signs, and stores bytes.
- This keeps remote functions lightweight even as share volume grows.

### 3) Lineage scaling

- First `resolveGraph(id)` call is proportional to lineage depth (walks ancestors).
- Subsequent calls for same head id are cache-backed from IndexedDB.
- Local and remote graph caches use separate prefixes to avoid namespace collision.

### 4) Product/code scaling

- Provider internals are composed from ports (`storage`, `crypto`, `graph`).
- New backends can be added by implementing ports and extending registry routing.
- UI and store call sites stay stable because the `DropProvider` interface does not change.

### Provider growth pattern

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  UI[Editor and dropStore call sites]
  Registry[DropProviderRegistry]
  Local[local]
  Remote[remote]
  NewScope[new scope]

  UI --> Registry
  Registry --> Local
  Registry --> Remote
  Registry -. add route .-> NewScope

  NewScope --> StoragePort[custom storage port]
  NewScope --> CryptoPort[crypto port]
  NewScope --> GraphPort[graph port]
```

### Scaling topology diagram

```mermaid
flowchart TB
  Traffic[Create/Get/Clone requests] --> Split{routing}
  Split -->|offline mode or offline_ id| LocalPath[Local provider path]
  Split -->|remote id| RemotePath[Remote provider path]

  LocalPath --> LocalCrypto[client-side crypto]
  LocalPath --> LocalStorage[IndexedDB persistence]

  RemotePath --> RemoteCrypto[client-side crypto]
  RemotePath --> EdgeFn[stateless Functions]
  EdgeFn --> ObjectStore[R2 object storage]

  LocalPath --> GraphCacheLocal[local graph cache]
  RemotePath --> GraphCacheRemote[remote graph cache]
```

## Operational boundaries and limits

- Offline links are local to the browser profile/device that created them.
- Remote sealed envelopes can only be opened by the matching account vault.
- Provider signature verification requires configured client verify key (`VITE_PROVIDER_SIGNING_PUBLIC_JWK`).
- Graph cache currently has no TTL/version invalidation policy.

## Failure modes to expect

- Local create fails if IndexedDB is unavailable.
- Remote create/get fails on network/API errors.
- Open fails when vault account does not match envelope account id.
- Open fails if device signature or provider signature verification fails.

## Extension recipe: add another provider scope

1. Implement storage semantics equivalent to `DropStoragePort`.
2. Reuse `BrowserDropCrypto` or add another `DropCryptoPort` implementation.
3. Reuse `LineageDropGraphPort` or provide a custom graph strategy.
4. Add provider instance to registry and define routing rule.
5. Keep `dropStore` public methods unchanged so UI remains provider-agnostic.

## Key file map

- `src/lib/drop/provider.ts` - provider contracts, implementations, registry
- `src/lib/drop/browserDropCrypto.ts` - envelope seal/open and signature verification
- `src/lib/drop/passkeyVault.ts` - vault keys, passkey gating, unlock cache
- `src/stores/dropStore.ts` - app-facing provider routing
- `src/pages/editor/hooks/useShareDrop.ts` - share payload composition
- `functions/api/store.ts` - remote store write path and optional provider signing
- `functions/api/get/[id].ts` - remote read path
- `shared/drop/types.ts` - payload/envelope schema and canonical serialization
